{
  "id": "dummy",
  "name": "Dummy Deck",
  "description": "Sandbox for testing new technical phrases before migration.",
  "deckType": "flippable",
  "cards": [
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_170",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "Cómo eras antes?",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "What were you like before?",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_170_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "How were you before?",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_170_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "What did you use to be like?",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_170_sideB_2.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": "**[er:86]**\n\n[What... like?] refers to past descriptions of character or appearance, whereas [How...?] refers to a past state or condition."
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_176",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "Lo que importa es que sea entendible.",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "What matters is that it's understandable.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_176_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "The important thing is that it's clear.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_176_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "All that matters is that it makes sense.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_176_sideB_2.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "What matters is it's understandable.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_176_sideB_3.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": "~What matters it's to be understandable~ is incorrect because it contains a redundant [it's]. The phrase [What matters] acts as the subject, so you should connect it directly to the verb [is], as in [What matters is that it's understandable].\n\n~What matters is to be understandable~ is unnatural. You need to specify what is being understandable. It is better to use a full clause like [is that it's understandable] or specify the object like [for it to be understandable]."
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_182",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "Ocurrio una desincronizacion en el procedimiento.",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "A desynchronization occurred in the procedure.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_182_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "A desync occurred in the procedure.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_182_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "An out-of-sync issue occurred during the procedure.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_182_sideB_2.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": "~It happened a desynchronization in the procedure.~ and ~It occurred a desynchronization in the procedure.~ are incorrect. In English, you cannot use [It] as a dummy subject to introduce an event in this way. You must either make the event the subject itself, like [A desynchronization occurred], or use [There was a desynchronization]."
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_188",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "Este producto sobra.",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "This product is extra.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_188_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "This product is left over.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_188_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "We have this product left over.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_188_sideB_2.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": "**[pv:203]**\n\n~This product is left~ is not entirely accurate for 'sobra'. [Left] means remaining ('queda'), while [left over] specifically means extra or surplus ('sobra')."
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_190",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "Está pendiente eso para mañana.",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "That's pending for tomorrow.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_190_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "That is pending for tomorrow.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_190_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "That remains pending for tomorrow.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_190_sideB_2.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "We left that for tomorrow.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_190_sideB_3.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "That's left for tomorrow.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_190_sideB_4.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": "\n\n~That's left over for tomorrow~ is incorrect because [left over] means extra or surplus, not pending. Use [pending] or [left]."
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_197",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "Aún no he tenido respuesta de él.",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "I haven't heard back from him yet.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_197_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "I still haven't received a reply from him.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_197_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "I haven't had a response from him yet.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_197_sideB_2.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "I haven't had an answer from him yet.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_197_sideB_3.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "I haven't heard anything from him yet.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_197_sideB_4.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": "**[er:103]**"
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_198",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "Aún no he sabido nada acerca de eso.",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "I haven't heard anything about that yet.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_198_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "I still haven't received any news regarding that.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_198_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "I haven't found out anything about that yet.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_198_sideB_2.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": "**[pv:59]**\n**[er:103]**\n\n~I didn't know anything about that yet~ and ~I haven't known anything about that yet~ are incorrect. Although 'know' translates to 'saber', in English [know] is a state verb (the condition of having knowledge), not an action verb. In Spanish, 'saber' can mean both the state ('yo sé') and the action of receiving news ('no he sabido nada'). In English, when you mean 'enterarse' or receiving an update, you must use action verbs like [hear] or [find out]. Therefore, you say 'I haven't heard' (no he tenido noticias) instead of 'I haven't known'. Additionally, [yet] typically pairs with the present perfect."
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_203",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "Aquí pasamos los números a formato texto.",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "Here we convert the numbers to text format.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_203_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "Here we pass the numbers into text format.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_203_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "In this step, we convert the numbers into text format.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_203_sideB_2.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "Here we transform the numbers to text format.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_203_sideB_3.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": "\n\n~Here we parse the numbers to text format.~ is not completely accurate. In programming, [parse] usually means analyzing a text string to extract data or convert it into a different type (like string to integer). To change a number into a text string, the correct terms are [convert], [cast], or [format]."
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_204",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "Para acelerar el proceso, ustedes deberian llamar directamente a Apple.",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "To speed up the process, you should call Apple directly.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_204_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "To expedite the process, you should call Apple directly.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_204_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "In order to speed up the process, you guys should call Apple directly.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_204_sideB_2.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "To speed the process, you should call Apple directly.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_204_sideB_3.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "To accelerate the process, you should call Apple directly.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_204_sideB_4.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": "~To speed up the process, you should call direcly to Apple~ is incorrect because the verb 'call' is transitive and connects directly to its object without [to]. It should be [call Apple directly].\n\n~To speed up the process, you should call directly apple~ is incorrect due to word order. In English, the adverb should go after the direct object, so it should be [call Apple directly]."
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_205",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "Ellos te pediran tu carnet de identidad para validar tu identidad.",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "They will ask for your ID card to validate your identity.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_205_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "They'll ask for your ID to verify your identity.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_205_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "They will request your ID card to confirm your identity.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_205_sideB_2.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": null
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_206",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "Solicite hablar con alguien que hablara en español.",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "I requested to speak with someone who speaks Spanish.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_206_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "I asked to speak to someone who could speak Spanish.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_206_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "I asked to talk to a Spanish speaker.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_206_sideB_2.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": "~I requested to speak with someone to speak spanish~ is incorrect because using the infinitive [to speak] implies purpose (in order to speak). To describe the person's ability, you must use a relative clause like [who speaks Spanish]."
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_207",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "Production stopper, Production blocker y Showstopper significan prácticamente lo mismo.",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "Production stopper, Production blocker, and Showstopper mean essentially the same thing.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_207_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "Production stopper, Production blocker, and Showstopper mean practically the same thing.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_207_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "Production stopper, Production blocker, and Showstopper are basically the same thing.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_207_sideB_2.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "Production stopper, Production blocker, and Showstopper mean basically the same.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_207_sideB_3.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": null
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_208",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "Production blocker y Showstopper son los más comunes de usar.",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "Production blocker and Showstopper are the most commonly used terms.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_208_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "Production blocker and Showstopper are the most common ones to use.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_208_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "Production blocker and Showstopper are used the most.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_208_sideB_2.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "Production blocker and Showstopper are the most common to use.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_208_sideB_3.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": null
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_209",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "Production stopper se entiende, pero se usan más Showstopper o Production blocker.",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "Production stopper is understood, but Showstopper and Production blocker are used more often.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_209_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "Production stopper is understood, but Showstopper or Production blocker are more commonly used.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_209_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "People understand Production stopper, but Showstopper and Production blocker are used more.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_209_sideB_2.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "Production stopper is understandable, but Showstopper and Production blocker are much more used.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_209_sideB_3.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "Production stopper is understood, but Showstopper or Production blocker are more used.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_209_sideB_4.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": null
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_210",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "Así podemos comenzar con el pie derecho.",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "That way we can start off on the right foot.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_210_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "This way we can get off on the right foot.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_210_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "So we can start on the right foot.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_210_sideB_2.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": "~So we can start with the right foot~ is incorrect because the standard English idiom uses the preposition [on], as in [start on the right foot]."
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_211",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "Prefiero una entrevista de uno a uno (2 personas).",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "I prefer a one-on-one interview.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_211_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "I would rather have a one-on-one interview.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_211_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "I'd prefer a one-to-one interview.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_211_sideB_2.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": "~I prefer an interview one-on-one~ uses incorrect word order. The phrase [one-on-one] functions as an adjective and must be placed immediately before the noun, as in [a one-on-one interview].\n\n~I prefer an one-on-one interview~ is incorrect because 'one' starts with a consonant sound ('w'), so you must use the article [a], not 'an'."
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_212",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "Testiando los casos uno a uno (un caso a la vez).",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "Testing the cases one by one.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_212_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "Testing the cases one at a time.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_212_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "Testing each case one by one.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_212_sideB_2.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": null
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_213",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "Lo testie sobre la marcha y funcionó.",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "I tested it on the fly and it worked.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_213_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "I tested it as I went and it worked.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_213_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "I tested it on the go and it worked.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_213_sideB_2.mp3"
        },
        {
