        {
          "text": "What's happening with today's meeting?",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_223_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "How about the meeting today?",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_223_sideB_2.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": "~What about the meeting of today?~ sounds unnatural. In English, we use the possessive form [today's] for time phrases, making it [today's meeting]."
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_224",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "¿Vamos a tener la reunión para hoy en la noche?",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "Are we going to have the meeting tonight?",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_224_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "Are we still having the meeting tonight?",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_224_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "Will we have the meeting tonight?",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_224_sideB_2.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": "~Will we have the meeting's tonight?~ is incorrect because you do not need a possessive ('s) for the meeting. The time phrase 'tonight' acts as an adverb modifying the verb, so it should be [have the meeting tonight].\n\n~Will we have the meeting for tonight?~ is unnatural because [tonight] already functions as an adverb of time. Adding the preposition [for] makes it sound like a direct translation from Spanish. It should be [have the meeting tonight]."
    },
