    {
      "cardId": "dummy_243",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "Tuve que cambiar la presentación en el momento.",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "I had to change the presentation on the fly.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_243_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "I had to change the slides on the fly.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_243_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "I had to adjust the presentation on the fly.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_243_sideB_2.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "I had to change the presentation on the spot.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_243_sideB_3.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "I had to change the presentation right then and there.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_243_sideB_4.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": "**[misc:11]**\n\n~I had to change the presentation at that time~ means you changed it during a specific past period, not spontaneously 'on the fly'.\n\n~I had to change the presentation in the time / on the time~ are grammatically incorrect. To express doing something spontaneously or immediately, you can use expressions like [on the spot] or [right then and there].\n\n~I had to change the presentation at the moment~ means you changed it \"right now\" in the present, not spontaneously during a past event.\n\n~I had to change the presentation on the moment~ is not a valid English expression. You can use [on the spur of the moment] or [on the spot].\n\n~I had to change the presentation in the moment~ usually implies being caught up in the emotion of an experience, rather than making a quick, spontaneous adjustment.\n\n~I had to change the presentation at that moment~ implies you changed it during a specific point in time in the past, but it lacks the improvisational, unplanned meaning of doing something [on the fly] or [on the spot]."
    },
