        }
      ],
      "note": "**[misc:12]**\n**[er:61]**\n\n~There's already a tool for that, let's not waste the time~ is slightly unnatural because we generally say [waste time] without the article [the] when talking about time in a general sense.\n\n~It exists already a tool for that~ is a direct translation from Spanish. In English, to declare the existence of something, you must use the existential 'there', as in [There is already a tool for that].\n\n~There's already a tool for that, let's don't waste any time~ is incorrect because [let's don't] is non-standard grammar. The correct negative form of 'let's' is [let's not].\n\n~There's already a tool for that, let's not loose any time~ contains a spelling error. The adjective 'loose' means not tight; the correct verb is [lose]. Additionally, in English we typically say [waste time] rather than 'lose time' in this context.\n\n~There's already a tool for that, let's don't loose any time~ combines the incorrect structure 'let's don't' with the misspelled word 'loose'. The correct form is [let's not waste]."
    },
